7 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
8 An Act relating to poor persons; directing the
Department of Human Services to publish annual
9 report; providing information the report shall
contain; authorizing the Department to include
10 contextual information; directing the Department to
submit the report and make report publicly available
11 on website; providing that the provisions shall be
carried out within existing appropriations; providing
12 that provisions shall not require department to
create new data systems or hire additional employees;
13 directing the Department to make reasonable efforts;
providing for codification; and providing an
14 effective date.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 271 of Title 56, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. The Department of Human Services shall, using existing
22 resources and data already collected by the Department, compile and
23 publish an annual report regarding program integrity and payment
24 accuracy within the child care subsidy program administered pursuant
Req. No. 17055 Page 1

1 to T itle 56 of the Oklahoma Statutes and Chapter 40 of Title 340 of
2 the Oklahoma Administrative Code.
3 B. The purpose of the report shall be to promote
4 accountability, identify potential improper payments, support high-
5 quality child care providers, and ensure public funds are directed
6 to services actually delivered to Oklahoma children and working
7 families.
8 C. The report shall, to the extent practicable using existing
9 data systems, include:
10 1. The payment error rate for the child care subsidy program,
11 if such rate is calculated by the Department or required by federal
12 reporting;
13 2. The total amount of overpayments identified during the
14 preceding fiscal year, including those associated with attendance
15 reporting discrepancies when such information is available;
16 3. The total amount of overpayments recovered during the
17 preceding fiscal year;
18 4. The number of provider investigations completed related to
19 the child care subsidy program;
20 5. The number of adverse actions taken against providers,
21 including suspensions, terminations, or disqualifications;
22 6. Any trends or risk factors identified by the Department
23 related to improper payments, including patterns that may indicate
24 inaccurate attendance reporting or other program vulnerabilities;
Req. No. 17055 Page 2

1 7. A summary of education, outreach, or technical assistance
2 provided by the Department to help child care providers maintain
3 compliance and avoid improper payments; and
4 8. The number of current daycare facilities to date, child care
5 capacity, the number of daycare facilities losses, and child care
6 capacity loss each year.
7 D. The Department may include any additional contextual
8 information necessary to accurately interpret the data provided in
9 the report and to highlight the performance of providers operating
10 in good faith compliance with program requirements.
11 E. The Department shall submit the report to the Governor, the
12 Speaker of the Oklahoma House of Representatives, and the President
13 Pro Tempore of the Oklahoma Senate no later than November 1 of each
14 year and shall make the report publicly available on the
15 Department's website.
16 F. The requirements of this section shall be carried out within
17 existing appropriations and shall not require the Department to
18 create new data systems or hire additional full-time employees.
19 G. As part of the annual report required by this section, the
20 Department shall, using existing licensing and administrative data
21 to the extent available, include information regarding the supply
22 and capacity of child care providers in this state, including:
23 1. The total number of licensed child care facilities operating
24 in the state during the reporting period;
Req. No. 17055 Page 3

1 2. The estimated licensed child care capacity statewide and by
2 region, to the extent such information is available;
3 3. The number of licensed child care facilities that opened
4 during the preceding fiscal year;
5 4. The number of licensed child care facilities that closed
6 during the preceding fiscal year;
7 5. The estimated reduction in licensed child care capacity
8 associated with such closures, to the extent practicable; and
9 6. A summary of information obtained by the Department
10 regarding the primary reasons for provider closures.
11 H. The Department shall make reasonable efforts, within
12 existing resources, to contact providers that have closed during the
13 reporting period to request voluntary feedback regarding the reasons
14 for closure. Participation by former providers shall be voluntary,
15 and nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require the
16 Department to obtain responses in every case.
17 I. Nothing in this section shall be construed to require the
18 creation of new data systems or mandatory surveys of providers.
19 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
